    "body": "Currently we pretend Electron is a component of Chromium, like this:\n\n```\nsrc/\n├── atom\n├── brightray\n├── base\n├── chrome\n├── content\n├── ui\n...\n```\n\nIt makes our source code look seamless with Chromium's ones, for example the headers:\n\n``` c++\n#include \"atom/browser/atom_browser_context.h\"\n#include \"atom/browser/atom_browser_main_parts.h\"\n#include \"base/files/file_util.h\"\n#include \"brightray/browser/inspectable_web_contents.h\"\n#include \"content/public/browser/navigation_entry.h\"\n```\n\nthe namespace and the header guard:\n\n``` c++\n#ifndef ATOM_BROWSER_NATIVE_WINDOW_H_\n#define ATOM_BROWSER_NATIVE_WINDOW_H_\n\nnamespace atom {\n}  // namespace atom\n\n#endif  // ATOM_BROWSER_NATIVE_WINDOW_H_\n```\n\nSo anyone familiar with Chromium's source code or Google C++ style guide can quickly understand the structure of our source code, and we are free to reuse the tools in Chromium like `cpplint`. And vice verso for developers of Electron who want to explore the source code of Chromium.\n\nSwitching to the `src` and `lib` style makes Electron more like a node module, but it is not true, Electron is more Chromium than Node.\n"
